NetWare 6.5 ZenPack v0.9 - 3/9/09
These templates were built against NW65SP7/OES2-NetWare servers. I have not tested against any other version, but NetWare 6.0 and earlier support packs of 6.5 *should* work.
Large portions of these templates are based on the AIX, NetApp and HP-UX ZenPacks developed by other Zenoss users.
MRTGEXT.NLM from http://forge.novell.com/modules/xfmod/project/?mrtgext must be installed and running on the NetWare servers.
SNMP and the standard in-the-box NetWare Management Agent must also be running (default is to have a SYS:\SYSTEM\NMA\NMA5.NCF command in the AUTOEXEC.NCF file).
MRTGEXT.NLM (on the NetWare side) and a perl script (Zenoss_NetWare_Stats.pl) on the Zenoss server (via ZenCommand) are used to gather most of the OS-related data, especially the memory statistics (which actually pull data from Novell Remote Manager/PORTAL.NLM on the backend). This may be overkill for some users (I was trying to see how much data I could gather).
Filesystem data is collected entirely via SNMP and a shell script using a dedicated NetWareFileSystemMap plugin for Modeling (because we have to calculate UsedBlocks). I decided to not use the standard Host Resources mib to gather the filesystem data because I don't want the server names included with the volume name in the listing - I am running multiple NetWare clusters. The _ADMIN volume is dropped from modeling (since its not a "real" volume).
Memory and Swap sizes are also modeled with dedicated modeling plugins (NetWareMemoryInfo and NetWareSwapInfo).
There are OS-related thresholds (Packet Receive Buffers reaching 90% of the server's Maximum Packet Receive Buffers setting for example) set in the Device template that refer to other gathered values - these are disabled because I have been unable to get them to work so far.
This is still a work in progress and will probably change when Zenoss 2.4 Blue Crab ships since the modeling process will be improved. I am hoping to be able to directly query against MRTGEXT.NLM instead of having to use a perl script to gather data for ZenCommand.
I am working on a NetWare Clustering ZenPack to go along with this one.
Template to gather OS data via MRTGEXT, Zenoss_NetWare_Stats perl script, and SNMP

${here/ZenPackManager/packs/ZenPacks.community.NetWare/path}/libexec/Zenoss_NetWare_Stats ${device/manageIp} S15 S16 S27 S26 NRMM:Total_System_Memory NRMM:File_System_Cache NRMM:NLM_Memory NRMM:In_Use_Kernel_Space NRMM:Available_Kernel_Space NRMM:Fragmented_Kernel_Space | sed 's/:/_/g'

${here/ZenPackManager/packs/ZenPacks.community.NetWare/path}/libexec/Zenoss_NetWare_Stats ${device/manageIp} NRMM:Used_By_Virtual_Memory_System NRMM:Available_Cache_Memory NRMM:Extended_Memory_In_Use NRMM:Reserved_User_Space NRMM:Total_Address_Space | sed 's/:/_/g'

This field may contain: MAY_NOT_SLEET_BIT-may not relinquish control, SORT_LOW_TO_HIGH_BIT-sort synchronous consumers so that consumers with the lowest order value are invoked first. CONSUMABLE_BIT-this event may be consumed. If consumed, subsequent consumable consumers will not be invoked for this event instance. NO_SA_BIT-A security authority is not allowed to register for this event. NO_AUDITOR_BIT-An auditor is not allowed to register for this event. If the size of the history is increased, no history data will be lost. If the size of the history is decreased, the oldest samples will be discarded as necessary.

The value of nwtHistorySampleIndex for the most recent sample in the associated history.
A value of 0 indicates that there is no history available for this variable.

The current state of history collection for this nwtControlEntry.
When the state is 'enabled', each sampled value will be added to the history.
When the state is 'disabled', sampled values will not be added to the stored history.

An index to be used to access the nwtHistoryTable to retrieve the stored samples for this variable. This value must remain constant at least from one re- initialization of the agent to the next re- initialization.

The value of the variable during the last sampling period. The value during the current sampling period is not made available until the period is completed.
Note that if the associated value nwtControlSampleType is set to 'deltaValue', the value of this object is the difference in the sampled variable since the last sample. If the value of nwtControlSampleType is 'averageValue', the value of this object is the average value of the selected variable over the sampling interval.

The absolute date and time (UTC) of the beginning of the history associated with this control entry, expressed as seconds since midnight on January 1, 1970. The timestamp of any sample in the history may be computed as follows:
nwtControlReferenceTimeStamp + (nwtHistorySampleIndex * intervalInSeconds)
A value of 0 indicates that there is no history available for this variable.

A threshold for the sampled variable. When the current sampled value is greater than or equal to this threshold, and the value at the last sampling interval was less than this threshold, and the value of nwtControlThresholdType is 'risingAlarm', a single trap will be generated.
After a a trap is generated, another such trap will not
be generated until the sampled value falls below this threshold and reaches the nwtControlFallingThreshold.

An enumeration which identifies the interval over which the data is sampled, compared with the rising and falling thresholds, and saved in the history.
Intervals will be aligned to the real world clock. For instance, hourly samples will be taken on the hour, 15- minute samples will be taken at n:00, n:15, n:30, and n:45, etc.
If a valid sample can not be taken for any reason (server down, excessive timer skew, etc.) then the sample value will be set to the invalid value. If the interval is changed, any associated history will be discarded and a new history collection commenced.

The value used to represent 'invalid' for this variable. Any sample of this variable having a value equal to the value of nwtControlSampleInvalidValue is not a valid sample and should be treated accordingly.

The method of sampling the selected variable and calculating the value to be compared against the thresholds.
If the value of this object is 'absoluteValue', the value of the selected variable at the end of the sampling interval will be compared directly with both the nwtControlRisingThreshold and the nwtControlFallingThreshold values.
If the value of this object is 'deltaValue', the value of the selected variable at the end of the sampling interval will be subtracted from its value at the end of the previous sampling interval, and the difference compared with both the nwtControlRisingThreshold and the nwtControlFallingThreshold values.
If the value of this object is 'averageValue', the average value of the selected variable over the sampling interval will be compared with both the nwtControlRisingThreshold and the nwtControlFallingThreshold values.

The current status of the attribute instance monitored by this nwtControlEntry.
As new volumes, disks, adapters, etc. are added to the server, entries for the new instances of each monitored attribute will automatically be added to this table, using appropriate default values for thresholds etc. From time-to-time, volumes, disks, adapters, etc. may also be permanently removed from the server; however, the entries for those instances in this table, and any associated histories, will continue to exist.
A value of 'valid' indicates that the instance defined by this nwtControlEntry is present in the server.
A value of 'invalid' indicates that the instance defined by this nwtControlEntry is no longer present in the server. Any associated history data is still available.
